## 1. Purpose

This Architecture Design Specification defines the durable architectural model
for {{ project_name }} and records the formal design items that implement that
model. The architecture bundles two complementary layers — an orchestration
layer and a reusable engine layer — in a single tooling repository so that
engineering execution and design-controlled structure stay connected without
becoming the same system.

## 2. Architectural Context

{{ project_name }} is delivered from a single tooling-first repository:

- `medharness` is the orchestration CLI, CI gate logic, and scaffolding system
- `dhfkit` is the reusable DHF engine for items, traceability, lifecycle, and document generation
- product repositories hold executable code, tests, and product CI workflows
- DHF repositories (generated from bundled templates) hold controlled requirements, architecture, risk, change, and evidence structure

The architecture exists to keep these responsibilities explicit. Product code
changes are driven by controlled design inputs, and DHF changes remain visible,
versioned, and auditable as first-class repository content.

## 3. Repository Boundaries and Responsibilities

### 3.1 Orchestration Layer (`medharness`)

`medharness` owns product-side orchestration concerns:

- onboarding and repository scaffolding through `medharness init`
- requirement-to-test coverage evaluation from JUnit evidence
- runtime evidence bundle generation from CI artifacts and repository state
- product-facing workflow conventions, including CR-aware CI and agent entrypoints

### 3.2 Engine Layer (`dhfkit`)

`dhfkit` owns DHF-side structural and design-control concerns:

- DHF document templates and controlled plan/spec documents
- item schemas, lifecycle rules, and required traceability paths
- item CRUD, validation, graph operations, and document generation
- repository content that scaffolds DHF-side workflows and agent guidance

### 3.3 Product Repo vs DHF Repo

The product repository is optimized for implementation and verification
execution. The DHF repository is optimized for controlled design records.
Neither repository is a projection of the other; they cooperate through shared
identifiers, explicit traceability links, CI contracts, and generated evidence.

## 4. Runtime Delivery Model

DHF repositories are scaffolded from bundled templates rather than fetched from
a separate source repo:

1. `medharness init` copies template assets from `medharness/templates/`.
2. The scaffolded DHF repository becomes the controlled starting point for a product program.
3. Product CI installs `medharness` (which includes `dhfkit`) and uses the commands against the DHF repository selected for that product.
4. Generated specification documents and evidence outputs are produced from the live DHF and CI artifacts at runtime.

This model keeps the tooling self-contained and allows the bundled templates to
evolve as the canonical source of structure and document templates within a
single repository.

## 5. Agent Guidance Model

AI-assisted workflows are grounded in documents and prompts rather than a
bundled harness payload. Guidance comes from:

- DHF-side formal documents such as the CRS, architecture specification, and development plan
- repo-local guidance files such as `CLAUDE.md`
- workflow prompts and automation-specific instructions stored with the relevant repository
- controlled item schemas and traceability requirements loaded through `dhfkit`

This model makes AI behavior easier to audit because the instructions that shape
agent work live in versioned repository content.

## 6. Durable Architectural Principles

The architecture follows these durable principles:

- design control is repository-native and traceability-first
- design records are constrained structurally before they are interpreted semantically
- product code and DHF content remain separated but explicitly linked
- runtime outputs such as generated specifications and evidence bundles derive from controlled source content
- the tooling ships as a single repository with clear layer boundaries between orchestration and engine

## 7. Major Components

### 7.1 Orchestration Layer

The orchestration layer contains:

- CLI commands that orchestrate scaffolding, coverage gating, evidence generation, and CR flows
- CI workflow templates written into product repositories
- adapter-facing logic that reads DHF structure without owning DHF content

### 7.2 Engine Layer

The engine layer contains:

- YAML-based DHF item storage and configuration
- `dhfkit` services for validation, lifecycle, graph traversal, and document generation
- controlled templates and plans that define the formal DHF document set

### 7.3 Verification and Evidence Interfaces

The boundary between implementation and formal evidence is carried by:

- JUnit XML with requirement linkage metadata
- CR identifiers shared across PRs, workflow automation, and DHF records
- generated evidence bundles assembled from runtime artifacts rather than prepacked release assets

